thoughts.reasoning_problem:
Context: Pets are allowed in some managed buildings. [BG] A deposit is required to rent an apartment in a managed building. The security deposit can be either equal to one month's rent or more. Fluffy is Tom's cat. Cats are pets. The Olive Garden is a managed building. The monthly rent at the Olive Garden is $2000. Tom will rent an apartment in a managed building if and only if he is allowed to move in with Fluffy, and the security deposit is no more than $1500. 2000$ is more than $1500.
Question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Tom will rent an apartment in The Olive Garden.
Options: A) True B) False C) Uncertain
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
PetsAllowed(x) ::: Pets are allowed in x.
ManagedBuilding(x) ::: x is a managed building.
DepositRequired(x) ::: A deposit is required to rent an apartment in x.
EqualOrMore(x, y) ::: The security deposit x can be either equal to one month's rent y or more.
Cat(x) ::: x is a cat.
Pet(x) ::: x is a pet.
Rent(x, y, z) ::: x will rent an apartment in y with a monthly rent of z.
MoveInWith(x, y) ::: x is allowed to move in with y.
LessOrEqual(x, y) ::: The security deposit x is no more than y.
More(x, y) ::: x is more than y.
Premises:
∃x (ManagedBuilding(x) ∧ PetsAllowed(x)) ::: Pets are allowed in some managed buildings.
∀x (ManagedBuilding(x) → DepositRequired(x)) ::: A deposit is required to rent an apartment in a managed building.
∀x ∀y (DepositRequired(x) → EqualOrMore(x, y)) ::: The security deposit can be either equal to one month's rent or more.
Cat(fluffy) ∧ Pet(fluffy) ∧ ∀x (Cat(x) → Pet(x)) ::: Fluffy is Tom's cat. Cats are pets.
ManagedBuilding(oliveGarden) ∧ Rent(oliveGarden, tom, 2000) ::: The Olive Garden is a managed building. The monthly rent at the Olive Garden is $2000.
∀x ∀y ∀z (Rent(x, y, z) ↔ (MoveInWith(y, fluffy) ∧ LessOrEqual(z, 1500))) ::: Tom will rent an apartment in a managed building if and only if he is allowed to move in with Fluffy, and the security deposit is no more than $1500.
More(2000, 1500) ::: 2000$ is more than $1500.
Conclusion:
Rent(tom, oliveGarden, 2000) ::: Tom will rent an apartment in The Olive Garden.

Fluffy is Tom's cat. Cats are pets. The Olive Garden is a managed building. The monthly rent at the Olive Garden is $2000. Tom will rent an apartment in a managed building if and only if he is allowed to move in with Fluffy, and the security deposit is no more than $1500. 2000$ is more than $1500.
Question: Based on the above information, is the following statement true, false, or uncertain? Tom will rent an apartment in The Olive Garden.
Options: A) True B) False C) Uncertain
raw_logic_programs:
Predicates:
PetsAllowed(x) ::: Pets are allowed in x.
ManagedBuilding(x) ::: x is a managed building.
DepositRequired(x) ::: A deposit is required to rent an apartment in x.
EqualOrMore(x, y) ::: The security deposit x can be either equal to one month's rent y or more.
Cat(x) ::: x is a cat.
Pet(x) ::: x is a pet.
Rent(x, y, z) ::: x will rent an apartment in y with a monthly rent of z.
MoveInWith(x, y) ::: x is allowed to move in with y.
LessOrEqual(x, y) ::: The security deposit x is no more than y.
More(x, y) ::: x is more than y.
Premises:
∃x (ManagedBuilding(x) ∧ PetsAllowed(x)) ::: Pets are allowed in some managed buildings.
∀x (ManagedBuilding(x) → DepositRequired(x)) ::: A deposit is required to rent an apartment in a managed building.
∀x ∀y (DepositRequired(x) → EqualOrMore(x, y)) ::: The security deposit can be either equal to one month's rent or more.
Cat(fluffy) ∧ Pet(fluffy) ∧ ∀x (Cat(x) → Pet(x)) ::: Fluffy is Tom's cat. Cats are pets.
ManagedBuilding(oliveGarden) ∧ Rent(oliveGarden, tom, 2000) ::: The Olive Garden is a managed building. The monthly rent at the Olive Garden is $2000.
∀x ∀y ∀z (Rent(x, y, z) ↔ (MoveInWith(y, fluffy) ∧ LessOrEqual(z, 1500))) ::: Tom will rent an apartment in a managed building if and only if he is allowed to move in with Fluffy, and the security deposit is no more than $1500.
More(2000, 1500) ::: 2000$ is more than $1500.
Conclusion:
Rent(tom, oliveGarden, 2000) ::: Tom will rent an apartment in The Olive Garden.
